    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hi, I'm looking into dietary management for a client who has been vegan for several years. They've recently had some bloodwork showing low B12 levels. Could you explain the biological mechanism of how B12 is actually absorbed in the digestive tract, specifically regarding the role of intrinsic factor in the stomach?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Vegans are at risk of B12 deficiency due to its exclusive dietary source being animal products. Intrinsic factor, a glycoprotein produced by the parietal cells in the stomach, plays a crucial role in the biological mechanism of B12 absorption. It binds to dietary B12 and forms a complex, which then facilitates the absorption of vitamin B12 in the duodenum and jejunum through a co-receptor called R-bound protein.",
      "source": "target",
