      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When vitamin B12 is not absorbed, the excess nutrients are deposited in various tissues, including the liver, muscles, and nerves. However, these excess nutrients can also be reabsorbed and utilized by the body. For example, liver cells can convert any excess B12 into methylcobalamin, which is then released into the circulatory system or stored in tissues. In the case of folate, excess nutrients can be recycled, but excessive amounts of other nutrients can be stored and potentially cause imbalance or toxicity.",
